---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Tournament & Competitive Scrabble — Guides & History"
  description="Everything about competitive Scrabble: tournament rules, ratings, famous matches, time management, and how to start competing. Free guides, no signup."
  keywords="scrabble tournament, competitive scrabble, scrabble ratings, tournament rules, world scrabble championship, how to play tournament scrabble, naspa scrabble"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do Scrabble tournaments work?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Scrabble tournaments use a Swiss-system pairing over multiple rounds (typically 8-24 games over 1-3 days). Players are matched based on similar records, and final standings consider both wins and cumulative point spread. Games use chess clocks with 25 minutes per player." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What rating do you need to play in a Scrabble tournament?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No minimum rating is required to enter most Scrabble tournaments. New players receive a provisional rating after their first event. Most national associations (NASPA, WESPA) welcome players of all skill levels, with divisions separating beginners from experts." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What dictionary is used in Scrabble tournaments?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "North American tournaments use the TWL (Tournament Word List, maintained by NASPA) with approximately 192,000 words. International tournaments use Collins Scrabble Words (CSW/SOWPODS) with approximately 280,000 words. The dictionary used depends on the organizing body." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 flex items-center gap-1">
      <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
      <span class="mx-1">›</span>
      <span class="text-gray-300">Tournament & Competitive</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Tournament & Competitive Scrabble</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 mb-4">
      From your first club night to the World Championship stage. These 13 guides cover tournament rules, 
      rating systems, famous matches, time management, preparation techniques, and the realities of competitive play. 
      Whether you're thinking about entering your first event or studying the history of the game's greatest moments.
    </p>
    <p class="text-base text-gray-400 mb-8">
      Competitive Scrabble is a world apart from kitchen-table games. Tournament players memorise tens of thousands of words, manage a chess clock with 25 minutes per side, track tiles mentally, and make split-second decisions under pressure. The community is welcoming to newcomers — most clubs have players at every level — but the jump from casual to competitive requires understanding specific rules (challenges, blank designation, clock protocol) and developing mental stamina for 8+ games in a day. These guides walk you through every stage: finding a local club, understanding rating systems like the NASPA system, preparing for your first rated event, studying famous games for inspiration, and building the psychological resilience that separates consistent winners from one-hit wonders.
    </p>

    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <a href="/blog/how-scrabble-tournaments-work/" class="block p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
